Nax

Target IP: 10.10.244.93

Identify the critical security flaw in the most powerful and trusted network monitoring software on the market, that allows an user authenticated execute remote code execution.

Reconnaissance


There are six TCP ports open on the target machine. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application.


The source-code of this HTML page contains a HTML comment hinting towards the directory /nagiosxi/, as shown above.


And browsing to /nagiosxi/ displays the webpage above. I tried to login with default credentials of this application but I had no luck. I performed a directory search to identify any hidden files but I had no luck. I got stuck at this point.


I notice the elements are from periodic table, so I did a search on the different names and made the table below:

  • Silver 47: /
  • Mercury 80: P
  • Tantalum 73: I
  • Antimony 51: 3
  • Polonium 84: T
  • Palladium 46: .
  • Mercury 80: P
  • Platinum 78: N
  • Lawrencium 103: G

Combining these character code leads to /PI3T.PNg. Is this a hidden file?


Browsing to http://10.10.244.93/PI3T.PNg shows the webpage above.


Using exiftool to extract metadata on this image shows the interesting information above. The Artist and Copyright are the most interesting to me.


I found an online tool that I can use to extract the hidden data inside the image from previous enumeration. The hidden data contains credential nagiosadmin:%n3p3UQ&9BjLp4$7uhWdY which is shown above.


And using the credential nagiosadmin:%n3p3UQ&9BjLp4$7uhWdY at https://10.10.244.93:443/nagiosxi/login.php was successful. It looks like the target machine is running Nagios XI 5.5.6 application. I know this application version is vulnerable to RCE which can be found at Metasploit.

Exploitation & Flags


I used Metasploit to exploit the target machine. The exploit module I used is exploit/linux/http/nagios_xi_plugins_check_plugin_authenticated_rce. In the picture above, I show the options I set for this exploit.


And firing the exploit landed me a root shell. No need to escalate my privileges!
